        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-20 17:49:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI think it is fine to include the position, even though it is inaccurate. This is still helpful for the admin, since it is possible the other operation statistics are inaccurate if the scan is restarted in the middle if the filesystem. \n\nThe fact that it is not updated frequently is not itself bad, so long as this is documented. Also, we might reduce the update interval in the future if it does not hurt performance.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d60324a9ef08c48690f2c9b29ba8b1819150ad64",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-20 17:51:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>  This is still helpful for the admin, since it is possible the other operation statistics are inaccurate if the scan is restarted in the middle if the filesystem.\n\nI thought LFSCK does store the counters in that file as well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ba6123b876eabe005e38730f23bd9f401d187816",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-05-21 00:46:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nConsider the following case:\n\n1) At time point_A, the administrator dump lfsck status: the scanned_objs is 'cA', the position is 'pA'.\n\n2) At another near time point_B, the administrator dump lfsck status again: this time the canned_objs is 'cB', but the position is still 'cA'.\n\nIf I am the administrator, I will suspect that it is Lustre BUG. Because I cannot imagine why some object has been scanned but position NOT moved? The time point_B depends on the frequency of the cached position to be updated and the schedule delay.\n\nOn the other hand, from the test view, updating the cached position by the lfsck engines itself may be NOT good, because there will be some \"fail_loc\" to make the lfsck engine to sleep sometime and slowdown the lfsck progressing. But such sleeping will affect the cached position updating, then many of test cases may need to be reconsidered and re-implemented.\n\nIn fact, although we will NOT update the cached position very frequently, we have to check (after each object scanned) that whether it is time to update the cached position. Although such check will not be much expensive, the total cost for all the scanned objects may cannot be ignored.\n\nSo my idea is that: if we have to dump the 'position' information, we should give a relative accurate position which will be updated together with the objects scanning to NOT confuse the administrator and simplify the test/implementation.\n\nCurrent mechanism and implementation is a \"lfsck\" status snapshot with very low cost, which will query the position only when requested.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "1bcb498a9711c5cae82cc91a51a497e54ea7bd84",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-21 02:32:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Current mechanism and implementation is a \"lfsck\" status snapshot with very low cost, which will query the position only when requested.\n\nbut high maintainance cost as the code is not clear at all.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "6a89e5240d6921e09386ab470a29a76a1b928db1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-05-21 02:56:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n>> Current mechanism and implementation is a \"lfsck\" status snapshot with very low cost, which will query the position only when requested.\n> but high maintainance cost as the code is not clear at all.\n\nHow about to add more detailed comment in the patch to explain?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "92e642995cc6fd9a4fc0fc2bf05cddd971419af0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-21 03:00:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI'd rather drop this as a whole, given this brings no functionality. the natural counters should be quite enough, IMHO. especially given you can check with df how many total objects LFSCK needs to scan, while interpretation of the position is more complicated. if we care about the administrator...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
